        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer458014298" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16188226254292180062"><i>How do you make a book that anyone will read out of lives as quiet as these?</i><br/><br/>Stegner did it. <br/><br/>We follow two married couples from their bright eyed 1930s youth to their retirement years. There&apos;s no razzle dazzle, no shocks or mysteries, no scandals or horrors . Their hurts are subtle and familiar.<br/><br/>The writing is solid and reflective and downright beautiful.<br/><br/>I found the story to be mostly about acceptance. Loving people even when you don&apos;t like them. Finding satisfaction in life even when your plans f</span>
  <span id="freeText16188226254292180062" style="display:none"><i>How do you make a book that anyone will read out of lives as quiet as these?</i><br /><br />Stegner did it. <br /><br />We follow two married couples from their bright eyed 1930s youth to their retirement years. There's no razzle dazzle, no shocks or mysteries, no scandals or horrors . Their hurts are subtle and familiar.<br /><br />The writing is solid and reflective and downright beautiful.<br /><br />I found the story to be mostly about acceptance. Loving people even when you don't like them. Finding satisfaction in life even when your plans fall through. Not settling, not feeling trapped or resentful, but just learning to be OK with your life and appreciating what you have instead of wasting your life obsessing over what you don't have. A curiously ordinary yet elusive concept.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="16188226254292180062" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


