    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3768790150" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3768790150" />
    <a title="J.K. Grice" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/72137025-j-k-grice"><img alt="J.K. Grice" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1507324623p2/72137025.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3768790150?book_show_action=true">Jan 24, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="J.K. Grice" class="user" itemprop="url" name="J.K. Grice" href="/user/show/72137025-j-k-grice">J.K. Grice</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/72137025-j-k-grice?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3768790150" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15555701494502491228">I could give all to Time except-except<br/>What I myself have held. But why declare<br/>The things forbidden that while the Customs slept<br/>I have crossed to Safety with? For I am There<br/>And what I would not part with I have kept.<br/><br/>~ROBERT FROST<br/><br/>The poem above stands as the epigraph to Wallace Stegner&apos;s last novel, CROSSING TO SAFETY. Published in 1987, this books chronicles the lives of two married couples, spanning the years of 1933-1972. Larry &amp; Sally Morgan meet Sid &amp; Charity Lang while living in Madison, Wis</span>
  <span id="freeText15555701494502491228" style="display:none">I could give all to Time except-except<br />What I myself have held. But why declare<br />The things forbidden that while the Customs slept<br />I have crossed to Safety with? For I am There<br />And what I would not part with I have kept.<br /><br />~ROBERT FROST<br /><br />The poem above stands as the epigraph to Wallace Stegner's last novel, CROSSING TO SAFETY. Published in 1987, this books chronicles the lives of two married couples, spanning the years of 1933-1972. Larry &amp; Sally Morgan meet Sid &amp; Charity Lang while living in Madison, Wisconsin during the Depression. Both men teach English literature at the University, and the couples form a friendship based on their chemistry, interests, and circumstances. With only one remaining living parent between them, the Lang's and Morgan's develop a close familial relationship that endures over the decades to come.<br /><br />And what of Frost's poem? Why did Stegner choose these particular lines to front his book? Because CROSSING TO SAFETY is at once about "nothing at all" and almost "everything there is", all rolled together. It's about the formation of our lives and the choices and challenges we face during that journey. Frost says that we have to surrender ourselves over time, but we still retain our life experiences; our memories, joys, loves, hates, regrets, triumphs, and accommodations. These cannot be withheld or taken from us, as if overseen by a customs agency. Time itself does take away our youth and ultimately our lives, but we also carry things "we will not part with," into finality and death. We do have the power to create our own safe havens, complete with our life treasures. Mortality exits for us all, but so does identity, hope, and love as the powerful play goes on. <br /><br />"Chaos is the law of nature; order is the dream of man."<br />~HENRY ADAMS<br /><br />I think this was a quote that summed up the theme of CROSSING TO SAFETY. Larry Morgan thought of it often during his life with Sally and the Langs. How does one fulfill their dreams, and yet overcome the adversity of chaos in life? We do so with honor and courage and perseverance. We do so with the love and support of our friends and families. And, we should do so appreciatively with the time we are allotted here on Earth. We can never control all of the unpredictable things that are headed our way, but we can carry on and live life to the fullest. Wallace Stegner knew how to write about these simple yet critical facets of our lives and the dynamics that come into play over time; nothing and everything all at once.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15555701494502491228" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


